Day Against Apartheid observed hy students

Jennifer Sikora
Staff Writer

A moment of silence hushed those gath-
ered in the William Pitt Union Ballroom
last night after Students For a Free South
Africa opened their meeting with a liba-

tion for 13 people reportedly killed recent-

ly in South Africa.

“It’s not enough to be angry,” said SFSA
President Thurston Winbush. “It’s about
doing something with that anger, coming
up with constructive changes.” People
must learn to break down the barriers of
what and who is seen as an enemy,
Winbush said at the event, which was held
in observance of the United Nation’s
International Day Against Apartheid.

“Nobody is born prejudiced. Prejudice is
a part of the socialization process,” said
speaker Mongezi S. Nkomo, a native South
African. Racism could be better under-
stood by looking at economic and social
structures, according Nkomo.

“The capitalist system encourages greed,
envy and competition,” Nkomo said.
Racism in the United States and South
Africa became a means to justify power
and the economic process of capitalism.

“Culture is a product of social relations
of empowerment,” Nkomo said. “When
we look at prejudice, it’s a product of dis-
crimination. But discrimination is not
wrong in itself.”

He said people discriminate every day,
such as deciding to eat red meat instead of

fish for dinner.

Nkomo said myths are created when a
person or group feels threatened by the
abilities of another. “We need to challenge
the way we look at relations between each
other  In order to struggle against
racism, tribalism and global oppression,
we need empathy and good will.”

He said principles of religion are often
used to justify oppression. “We need to
fight against religion that is used like a
drug  there are people who defend capi-
talism with the Bible.”

Nkomo said as capitalism works its way
into South Africa, many people will not be
poor because of racism but because of the
economic system.

