THE PITT NEWS, Thursday, March 17, 1994

Low self esteem hinders one’s ability to change

In my last column I wrote that
many of us get “stuck” in our
lives in a variety of ways. We
are unhappy and want to find a
new direction for ourselves but
we find it difficult to do so. To
some extent this is because we
have come to believe that
change is painful and some-
thing » to be feared.
Consequently we resist, avoid
and block change in a multi-
tude of ways.

We construct elaborate barri-
ers to protect ourselves from
the pain we believe change
would bring us. One of the
most powerful internal obsta-
cles to change is low self-
esteem. If we do not value our-
selves then we are not likely to
believe that we deserve a better
life.

it is the voice within us that
says “no you can’t,” “you are
not good enough,” “you are not
smart enough,”“you are not
pretty enough,” and so you had
better just settle for the life you

have.
Low self—esteem damages us
in many ways. It makes us

underestimate our capabilities
and fear the exposure of our
real self. It also helps sustain
our self—fulfilling negative
expectations and often traps us
in an endless cycle of despair.
Low self—esteem usually has
its roots in early childhood
experiences. If we lived in an
atmosphere that was character-
ized by excessive criticism from
significant people in our lives

 

or if we lived in a family filled
with domestic violence, alco-
holism or abuse, then we are
likely to reach adulthood with a
damaged view of ourselves.

As adults, however, we are
capable of recovering from this
early damage and developing a
better self view. We need to
fight the fear that changing will
only make things worse and
open our minds to the possibili-
ty that we can develop a more
accepting view of self.

Seeking some professional
counseling is one way of
addressing this problem but
there is also a lot you can do on
your own. For example, one
strategy for building self—esteem
is to find models or mentors
who seem to be happy with
their lives and who demonstrate
positive self-esteem by the
behavior they exhibit. These
people are all around us and
they are not necessarily the best
looking, the slimmest, the
smartest or the most athletic.

They are, however, people who
use what they have in creative
and positive ways.

Find these people and study
them. Try to understand what
traits they have or how they
think about things that make
them happier and more accept-
ing of themselves. Most of our
own behavior and ways we
think about things were learned
from other people, but when
we were younger we didn’t
have much to say about who
the significant people were in
our lives.

Now you are capable of
choosing your own models. I
recommend that you do this
and not be afraid to begin prac-
ticing some of those behaviors
that you observe in these peo-
ple that you admire.

-I have written before that a
good way of becoming a suc-
cessful student is by imitating
one. I think that the advice
holds for a lot of other mea-
sures of success as well.

