with club

ByJ.M. Gonzalez
For The Pitt News

For the various English majors
and faculty there is one place
where both can meet. Pitt’s
Undergraduate English Club
allows English majors to meet
the faculty on a more social
level.

The English Club “takes down
the barriers of college,” said
senior Ron Murphy, co-chair of
the group.

“It fosters a relationship
between the teachers and stu-
dents on an academic level,”
said Murphy. “You can talk to
teachers as peers.”

The English Club organized
the second undergraduate poet-
ry reading at Hemingway’s yes-
terday.

It is part of Hemingway’s
poetry reading series in which
usually only graduate, faculty
and local writers participate.

The reading was arranged by
Anna Henderson, a senior, who
also read her poetry.

Aside from the undergraduate
poetry reading, the English Club
is trying to assemble a discus-
sion forum to raise awareness
on censorship and perspectives
taken by journalists.

According to Henderson, the
discussion would include cur-
rent censorship involving cam-
pus groups, banned books and
the media. The discussion forum
would tentatively be between
student groups, he said.

In the future, the English Club
will set up a Seminar Day for
English majors to help their
major work for them.

Co-chair Fred Bigelow, a
junior, is organizing a fiction
writing workshop where stu-
dents can critique each other’s
work outside. of the classroom.

The club is also planning a co-
op program between poetry
majors and high schools.

According to Murphy and
Henderson, the program would
involve poetry majors teaching

M poetry workshops.

A trip to Stratford, Ontario,
Canada — a_Shakespearian
town — is also underway.

According to the club’s faculty
advisor, Carol Kayes, the English
Club Was established about
three-and-half years ago to
allow the various undergraduate
English majors to meet each
other.

The group is “both a recre-
ational and an educational
club,” said Henderson.

On the recreational side, the
club sees plays and movies
together because they “provide
a common interest,” said
Murphy. _

The English Club is “goo
because you get to know the
faculty on a really small level,”
said Henderson.

