“I was very, very pleased,” Myers said
after the event. “It was stressful but well
worth it all at the end.”

“I was very honored to represent my
house and I’d like to thank them for sup-
porting me because I couldn’t have done
it without them,” Myers added.

The event, which kicked off 1994
Greek Week, consisted of representatives
from 27 fraternities and sororitites com-
peting for trophies and points towards
Greek Week.

According to Greek Week Overall Chair
Cassi Berarducci, Greek God and
Goddess raised close to $3,000 for Special
Olympics.

“Every contestant must have a $100
sponsor and in return they must incorpo-
rate the sponsors name with their toga
outfit,” Berarducci said.

Some of the acts featured in last night’s
event ranged from Broadway classics like
“The Music of the Night” from Phantom

of the Opera, sung by Nick Sacobs of
Theta Chi, to “The Beer Barrel Polka” per-
formed on the accordion by Mark
Dubravec of Delta Phi.

Contestants were judged by five indi-
viduals who based their decisions on
three categories.

The first is participation, which includes
attendance at meetings and tuming in the
sponsors’ money on time, and is worth 20
percent of the overall score.

The second part is the toga competition
which also counts for 20 percent. “The
toga competition is based on how well
the person incorporates the sponsor into
their toga and how the toga appearance is
overall,” said Greek God and Goddess
Chair JJ. Seiler.

The third and final category, which
counted for the last 60 percent of the
scores, was the talent competition. This
portion of the event was based on how
well the contestants presented themselves
to the audience and how well they per-
formed.

According to several students who
attended the event, some of the partici-

pants performed very well.

“It was awesome,” Nicole Walz said.
“The judging relies more on talent then
on looks. It was better competition than
people might think  each house got to
show off their stuff.”

Pitt junior Tom Bailer said he was
impressed with the level of talent he saw
during the competition. “I thought it was
great,” Bailer said. “The guy from Sigma
Phi Epsilon did a drill team routine that
was exceptional, and the brother who
played the accordion was outstanding.”

Greek Week business manager Kelly
Reddy said she was pleased with the
crowd in attendance last night. “It is a
great honor and I think that is why we
have so many people in the audience
because they truly support the brothers
and sisters who represent them.”

However, some people who attended
last night’s event had some criticism
about the show’s length, which lasted
over four-and-a-half hours. “It was too
long,” student Jim Dockey said. “They
should make it about three hours shorter,
[or] at least get rid of the toga part.”

