Picture this: A doctor begins a regime of treatment on
a patient using the latest research results. With these
new methods, it appears that not only will the patient
be cured, but they will have a higher standard of living
than if conventional treatments are used. Now imagine
that that it comes to light that some of the research was
falsified. Can this be tolerated in the life and death
field of medicine, or for that matter in any research that
is supposed to reveal the truth?

This is more than a hypothetical case. It turns out
that results were falsified in a breast cancer study
whose results were published in the New England

journal of Medicine in 1985. One doctor who partici-

pated in the National Surgical and Adjuvant Breast and
Bowel Project falsified approximately 100 of his cases.
The results of this report are supposedly unaffected by
the data given by this doctor, but so far it has only
been reviewed by people who have been directly asso-
ciated with this project (New Yorle Times).

The research study found that women with breast
cancer who had mastectomies (full breast removal) had
survival rates which were equivalent to those who had
lumpectomies and followed them with radiation thera-
py. This report was published in 1985, and many doc-
tors used thisas a basis for outlining treatment for their
patients. .

In 1991, it finally came out that there were cases
which had been falsified. The Federal Office of
Research Integrity examined the cases for two years.
The fact that research was falsified should have led to
nearly immediate warnings that doctors should have
received. It is important that proper information is used
in diagnosis and treatment of patients. Only now,
according to yesterday’s New Yorle Times, is the
National Cancer Institute appointing three independent
researchers to examine whether these falsified results
may have skewed the data to lead to erroneous con-
clusions.

While anyone can see the importance of examining
the data carefully before setting off alarms that could
lead to panic, it is nevertheless important that as soon
as it is discovered research data has been falsified that
independent groups begin to look at what effect this
data has on the conclusions.

Beyond this fact, there is also the need for proper
procedures for reading and review of research informa-
tion. Although everyone should have a strong sense of
responsibility and should work to maintain intellectual
integrity on their own, some amount of looking over‘
each other’s shoulders should occur in scholarly cir-
cles. This should not only happen in science, where it
is easiest, but also in the humanities and social sci-
ences, where the grey areas that are studied often have
an effect on people which, while it may not be life or
death, is as dear to them as their health.

