Rand argued. In 1981, Morton
Grove, Ill. banned the sale and possession of
handguns, period. In every court challenge to
that action, the law was upheld. “States are not
prohibited by the Second Amendment from con-
trolling private ownership of handguns and
other categories of firearms in virtually any way
they see fit,” Rand concluded.

Where do we go from here? Liberal and con-
servative philosophies have both been tried.

What exactly are handguns? They are sport-
ing goods legally available for sale, which have
the potential to be incredibly dangerous. If any
other consumer good caused 35,000 deaths, the
federal government would act.

The Consumer Product Safety Commission is
the agency that should become involved. Its
congressional mandate is to “protect the public
from unreasonable risks of injury from consumer
products.” In its 1990 annual report, the CPSC
banned 24 separate items from a general group
of 15 product categories that had caused 5,404
deaths. ‘

As the “Cease Fire” study pointed out, the time
has come to invest in feasible new ideas.
Manufacturers need to be motivated through the
responsibility of regulation. Research on how to
make handguns safer, the outright ban of
destructive accessories (armor piercing arnmuni—
tion, and laser sights, for example) and educa-
tion to save the next generation are but a few of
the new ideas that should be tried by the federal
government. Regulating where these weapons
can be purchased is another necessary step.

We owe it to the future to take care of a
problem of our own making. Thirty-five thou-
sand deaths a year is not much of an endorse-
ment for Plan A (what we're doing now). The
“Cease Fire” study presents a Plan B that’s worth
an honest try.

