Spencer’s vocals are reminis-
cent of Screaming Jay Hawkins:
whooping, barking, snarling
and pouting. Although the lyrics
are largly unintelligible, they are
delivered with authority and
display a keen sense of dynam-
ics. His guitar playing is loud
and spastic  John Lee Hooker
on crystal meth. It plods
through the rhythm, and
screams furiously like an
ensemble of power tools in the
solos. Spencer uses a Theremin,
a strange feedback device to
achieve these signature bursts.

Judah Baur’s guitar is equally
intense. His style is aggressive,
nearly savage. He plays hard,
real hard. Herb Hitts from Bad
Vibe magazine, in the liner
notes for Extra Width,
described Judah with “hands all
blurred, professor of his own
six—string style.” He ravages
through the songs, giving their
structure a gnarled, command-
ing edge. He creates a full
sound, solid as granite, which
leaves no room for a bass gui-
tar. The Blues Explosion is bass-
less, and doesn’t regret it.

One of the most undeniable
forces of the Explosion’s sound
is Russel Simin’s drumming. As
idiosyncatic as Spencer and
Bauer are, Sirnin’s drums are

powerful. His playing is so
straightforward, tight and
heavy, it’s frightening. The idea
is simple: be commanding, hot
flashy, and hit the drums hard.
As overwhelming as he sounds,
he does not overshadow the
rest of the band. He anchors
them down and keeps them
from sputtering out of control.

The band smokes. Their crazy
rock and roll sound shakes,
shimmies and thunders. It’s “hot
and cold at the same time,” rag-
ing in every direction. The band
has released several albums,
most notably Extra Width, their
latest.

Spin magazine considered it
one of the top—ten best albums
that you have never heard. A
recent 7-inch adds to John
Spencer Blues Explosion mania,
as does a video for “Afro,” from
Extra Width which appears on
MTV.

