Clarks over the past few years
most likely knows what to
expect when they go see the
band live: nothing really fancy
(smoke machines and fireworks
don’t fit Very well in The
Decade or Nick’s Fat City), just
tons of solid, energetic, catchy
rock ‘n roll tunes. I

Love Gone Sour, .Sztspz'cion
and Bad Debt, The Clarks’ first
album since late 1991, is an
almost perfect summary of the
band’s live shows over the past
few years. Though not a live
album, Love does all it can to
show anyone who’s too young
to get into Pittsburgh’s rock ‘n
roll clubs just what they’ve been
missing.

Love is filled with several
songs which have been staples
of The Clarks’ live shows in the
past. Singer Scott Blasey and
company have been belting out
“Treehouse,” “Cigarette,” “Climb
Down” and “Better Day” for
quite some time now.

. Despite the familiarity of most
of the 14 tracks on Love, The
Clarks have been making a
good deal of musical growth
lately. The clang ‘n twang of

Robert James‘ guitar still echoes
back pretty strongly to pre-MTV
R.E.M., but Love undoubtedly
contains The Clarks’ most pro-
gressive work yet.

“Promised Land,” a mysteri-
ous look at commitment and
revenge (“I’ve been tried and
convicted, you’re sending me
away/but I’ll have the last
inscription on judgment day”),
opens with a melancholy,
Doors-y guitar lead which grad-
ually builds up into the song’s
crashing chorus.

Unlike ‘91’s The C/arles, which

contained plenty of straightfor-

ward rock songs (“If I Fall
Through,” “Thought It Was
Free,” “Train of Love”) and one
acoustic ballad (“Penny on the
Floor”), Love contains more of
a musical variety. Pounding
rockers “Behind My Back” and
“Better Day” are offset by some
rather subdued songs such as
“Let You Go” and “Madeline.”
The band even gets down-
right mellow at times. The dark,
haunting “Madeline” is another
song based on what appears to
be Blasey’s favorite subject:
screwed-up romances. The

closing lyrics, “Tell her that you
mind the way she crosses her
heart and says I hope to die/I
guess I’ll never know you/I
guess I’ll never know why,”
could make one wonder if
Blasey has been listening to
Sting lately. And, for those fans
of the “unplugged" craze, The
Clarks even throw in an
acoustic version of “I’m The
Only,” which first appeared on
their 1988 debut, I’ll Tell You
What, Man.

Loves finest moments, how-
ever, are those which make one
feel like they’re actually sitting
at one of those miniscule round
tables on a dark, smoky night at
Graffiti. The only things missing
from “Tell Me” "and “Cigarette”
are Blasey’s ad~libs and beer-
chugging crowds singing along
with the chorus.

Accurately capturing the ener-
gy of 21 bands live show on disc
is usually a major accomplish-
ment. To do this on an album
recorded in the studio is noth-
ing short of incredible.

Gimme a smoke, man!

